^B@2^*BEddie Kantar: ^*N|cp||at|There are three ways to attack this contract after winning the @SA at trick one. (See 'Bottom Line' on why you should not duck the opening lead). |
PG| ***** 206 ***** |


NT|^B@2
1. The technical line: Cross to a high heart (in case there's a singleton @HQ about), unblock the @CA K Q, and take the heart finesse. |
PG| ***** 207 ***** |


NT|^B@2
2. The thief's line: Lead the @DJ at trick two hoping West has the @DA and ducks the trick. If he does, you have stolen trick ##9. |
PG| ***** 208 ***** |


NT|^B@2
3. The insulting line: Cash the @CA K Q, cross to dummy with a heart and play two more clubs hoping the player with five spades discards one of them. |
PG| ***** 209 ***** |


NT|^B@2
If that happens, you can knock out the @DA safely as the opponents will only have a maximum of three spades to cash. So which line would you like to opt for? |
PG| ***** 210 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Line 3 is the weakest. The player with five spades would have to make a gross error to discard a spade on the clubs. |
PG| ***** 211 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Line 2 has a chance. If West has something like @SJ x x x x and the @DA, he may not have realized that he has struck gold with the opening lead and may duck the @DJ hoping his partner can win with the hoped for @DQ to lead a spade through. |
PG| ***** 212 ***** |


